# 1. USE ENVIRONMENT VARIABLES:
#    In production, use your platform's environment variables instead of files:
#    - GitHub Secrets for CI/CD
#    - AWS Secrets Manager for AWS
#    - Google Cloud Secret Manager for GCP
#    - Azure Key Vault for Azure
#
# 2. SECRET ROTATION:
#    - Rotate all secrets every 90 days
#    - Monitor secret usage
#    - Revoke unused credentials
#
# 3. LOCAL DEVELOPMENT:
#    - Copy: cp .env.example .env.local
#    - Modify for your local setup
#    - Never commit .env.local to Git
#    - Use test/dummy credentials only
#
# 4. ENVIRONMENT-SPECIFIC FILES:
#    - .env.development   (defaults for development)
#    - .env.staging       (defaults for staging)
#    - .env.production    (defaults for production)
#    - .env.local         (your local overrides)
#    - .env.local.staging (local staging overrides)
#
# 5. VARIABLE SUBSTITUTION:
#    - Use ${VAR_NAME} for required variables
#    - These MUST be defined in .env.local or environment
#    - Example: JWT_SECRET=${JWT_SECRET}
#
# 6. OPTIONAL VS REQUIRED:
#    - [REQUIRED] = Application will not work without it
#    - [OPTIONAL] = Has sensible default, can be omitted
#    - [SECRET] = Sensitive value, keep secure
#
# 7. TESTING DIFFERENT SCENARIOS:
#    - Payment testing: Use Stripe test keys
#    - Email testing: Use Mailhog
#    - OAuth testing: Use test OAuth apps
#    - API testing: Use API test credentials
